\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/coreutils.html#od-s'\fB\-s\fP\X'tty: link'
same as \fB\-t\fR d2, select decimal 2\-byte units
.TP
\X'tty: link https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/coreutils.html#od-x'\fB\-x\fP\X'tty: link'
same as \fB\-t\fR x2, select hexadecimal 2\-byte units
.SS "TYPE is made up of one or more of these specifications:"
.TP
a
named character, ignoring high\-order bit
.TP
c
printable character or backslash escape
.TP
d[SIZE]
signed decimal, SIZE bytes per integer
.TP
f[SIZE]
floating point, SIZE bytes per float
.TP
o[SIZE]
octal, SIZE bytes per integer
.TP
u[SIZE]
unsigned decimal, SIZE bytes per integer
.TP
x[SIZE]
hexadecimal, SIZE bytes per integer
.PP
SIZE is a number.  For TYPE in [doux], SIZE may also be C for
sizeof(char), S for sizeof(short), I for sizeof(int) or L for
sizeof(long).  If TYPE is f, SIZE may also be B for Brain 16 bit,
H for Half precision float, F for sizeof(float), D for sizeof(double),
or L for sizeof(long double).
.PP
Adding a z suffix to any type displays printable characters at the end of
each output line.
.SS "BYTES is hex with 0x or 0X prefix, and may have a multiplier suffix:"
.TP
b
512
.TP
KB
1000
.TP
K
1024
.TP
MB
1000*1000
.TP
M
1024*1024
.PP
and so on for G, T, P, E, Z, Y, R, Q.
Binary prefixes can be used, too: KiB=K, MiB=M, and so on.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B od -A x -t x1z -v
Display hexdump format output
.TP
.B od -A o -t oS -w16
The default output format used by od
